health care dollars are spent, there is much less evidence on how this spending affects health.              The research in Measuring and Modeling Health Care Costs seeks to connect our knowledge of expenditures with what we are able to measure of results, probing questions of methodology, changes in the pharmaceutical industry, and the shifting landscape of physician practice. The research in this volume investigates, for example, obesity's effect on health care spending, the effect of generic pharmaceutical releases on the market, and the disparity between disease-based and population-based spending measures. This vast and varied volume applies a range of economic tools to the analysis of health care and health outcomes. Practical and descriptive, this new volume in the Studies in Income and Wealth series is full of insights relevant to health policy students and specialists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aMedical carezUnited StatesxCost control. 0aMedical care, Cost ofzUnited StatesxMeasurement. 4ahealth costs. 4ahealth outcomes. 4amarket design. 4apharmaceuticals. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aAizcorbe, Ana, eeditor.1 aBaker, Colin, eeditor.1 aBerndt, Ernst R., eeditor.1 aCutler, David M., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226530994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226530994.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles